WEBVTT

00:01.460 --> 00:04.463
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:04.463 --> 00:11.553
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.182 --> 00:16.808
<i>‐ My name is Chris VanGoethem.</i>

00:16.808 --> 00:18.852
<i>I'm from Stevens Point,</i>
<i>Wisconsin.</i>

00:18.852 --> 00:20.312
My son and I
started taking a class

00:20.312 --> 00:21.772
with a local farrier
blacksmith,

00:21.772 --> 00:22.898
<i>and my son got hooked,</i>

00:22.898 --> 00:24.149
<i>and I got hooked</i>
<i>right along with him,</i>

00:24.149 --> 00:26.068
and before we knew it,
we were making blades.

00:26.068 --> 00:27.819
<i>I don't think I'm competitive.</i>

00:27.819 --> 00:29.655
<i>I just think</i>
<i>I should win all the time.</i>

00:29.655 --> 00:31.281
[laughs]

00:31.281 --> 00:33.450
<i>‐ I'm Randy Cass, and I'm</i>
<i>from a little town,</i>

00:33.450 --> 00:35.160
<i>Liberty, Mississippi.</i>

00:35.160 --> 00:38.455
I was a farrier
for about 15 years,

00:38.455 --> 00:42.292
<i>and later on I picked up</i>
<i>the bladesmithing.</i>

00:42.292 --> 00:43.502
<i>Being 60 years old,</i>

00:43.502 --> 00:45.254
I've been through a lot
of pressure points,

00:45.254 --> 00:48.507
so pressure really
doesn't bother me.

00:48.507 --> 00:52.219
<i>‐ My name is Dan Strang.</i>
<i>I'm 18 years old.</i>

00:52.219 --> 00:54.429
I started bladesmithing
when I was 13,

00:54.429 --> 00:58.058
<i>and I really started getting</i>
<i>serious a couple years ago.</i>

00:58.058 --> 00:59.851
<i>I'm definitely</i>
<i>the youngest one here,</i>

00:59.851 --> 01:01.520
<i>but I love</i>
<i>being underestimated.</i>

01:01.520 --> 01:03.563
It's one of my favorite things.

01:03.563 --> 01:05.023
<i>‐ My name is Grover Clifton.</i>

01:05.023 --> 01:06.900
<i>I'm from Collinsville,</i>
<i>Oklahoma.</i>

01:06.900 --> 01:08.318
I am extremely competitive.

01:08.318 --> 01:11.488
I've competed in sports
my whole life.

01:11.488 --> 01:13.031
<i>I think that my strength</i>
<i>in bladesmithing</i>

01:13.031 --> 01:17.369
<i>would probably be forging</i>
<i>just because I'm strong.</i>

01:17.369 --> 01:19.454
I am my own power hammer.

01:19.454 --> 01:22.374
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to The Forge.

01:22.374 --> 01:24.543
You're here to engage
in three rounds of timed

01:24.543 --> 01:27.129
edged weapon‐making competition
specifically designed

01:27.129 --> 01:30.173
to test every aspect of
your bladesmithing capabilities

01:30.173 --> 01:32.134
in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:32.134 --> 01:33.302
that tells us which of you

01:33.302 --> 01:35.053
is the next
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:35.053 --> 01:37.889
leaving here with a check
for $10,000.

01:37.889 --> 01:39.308
Let's go ahead
and meet your judges now.

01:39.308 --> 01:43.520
Up first, two‐time "Forged
in Fire" champion Ben Abbott.

01:43.520 --> 01:46.064
Next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist

01:46.064 --> 01:47.232
David Baker,

01:47.232 --> 01:51.570
and last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:51.570 --> 01:54.573
Bladesmiths,
today we want to see a blade

01:54.573 --> 01:57.326
that's born
of pure imagination,

01:57.326 --> 01:58.910
so in the first round
of competition,

01:58.910 --> 02:01.038
we'd like you to use
your imagination

02:01.038 --> 02:03.415
to forge for us
a fantasy blade

02:03.415 --> 02:06.043
that is between 12
and 14 inches in length,

02:06.043 --> 02:09.129
and the overall length
must not exceed 22 inches.

02:09.129 --> 02:11.089
<i>‐ I'm like, "Whoa, awesome."</i>

02:11.089 --> 02:13.133
When you make a fantasy blade,
you aren't stuck

02:13.133 --> 02:15.344
to the confines
of historical accuracy.

02:15.344 --> 02:17.429
It can be anything
you want it to be.

02:17.429 --> 02:19.222
‐ Now, in the second round
you'll attach handles

02:19.222 --> 02:21.516
to those blades, turning them
into fully functional weapons

02:21.516 --> 02:24.227
that will be tested
for strength and durability

02:24.227 --> 02:28.440
in a armor chop and for edge
retention in a denim bag slice.

02:28.440 --> 02:29.608
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:29.608 --> 02:32.152
Since you're making
out‐of‐this‐world blades,

02:32.152 --> 02:35.405
here's some out‐of‐this‐world
metal to deal with.

02:35.405 --> 02:39.618
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:39.618 --> 02:41.453
That is meteorite.

02:41.453 --> 02:42.537
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:42.537 --> 02:44.790
<i>‐ I have never used meteorite</i>
<i>in my life.</i>

02:44.790 --> 02:46.750
I didn't even know
you could buy it.

02:46.750 --> 02:49.211
‐ Gentlemen, you must combine
this meteorite

02:49.211 --> 02:52.964
that is entirely mild steel
with 1095 powder

02:52.964 --> 02:55.258
to create a canister
Damascus billet

02:55.258 --> 02:56.468
from which
to forge your blades.

02:56.468 --> 03:01.807
‐ Fantasy blade, okay.
Canister, not ideal.

03:01.807 --> 03:05.394
Meteorite?
I have no clue.

03:05.394 --> 03:07.145
‐ You'll have ten minutes to
work on your design.

03:07.145 --> 03:09.398
You'll have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:09.398 --> 03:11.233
I remind you that
after the judges

03:11.233 --> 03:12.651
have inspected your work,

03:12.651 --> 03:15.487
one of you will have
to surrender your fantasy knife

03:15.487 --> 03:18.115
and leave The Forge.
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:18.115 --> 03:20.951
Your ten‐minute design window
starts now.

03:20.951 --> 03:27.290
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:27.290 --> 03:28.667
‐ Fantasy blades.

03:28.667 --> 03:31.169
‐ Because it's fantasy, man.
You can go crazy with that.

03:31.169 --> 03:34.965
Just remember that it's gonna
be wielded by human characters.

03:34.965 --> 03:37.759
‐ Yeah, we want something that
is elegant, fantastical,

03:37.759 --> 03:40.095
but also has a functional
element to it, correct?

03:40.095 --> 03:41.888
‐ Yeah.
<i>‐ Fantasies are hard,</i>

03:41.888 --> 03:44.433
'cause I don't watch fantasy TV
or nothing like that,

03:44.433 --> 03:47.727
<i>but I'm trying to put</i>
<i>a fish design,</i>

03:47.727 --> 03:49.688
<i>a fish tail on my drawing</i>

03:49.688 --> 03:53.191
<i>and have a swell in the middle</i>

03:53.191 --> 03:57.529
<i>and sharpen it</i>
<i>on three sides on the end.</i>

03:57.529 --> 03:58.905
What is fantasy?

03:58.905 --> 04:03.452
You know, this could be
my fantasy, a fish mouth.

04:03.452 --> 04:06.705
‐ I don't make fantasy blades,
but I came on "Forged in Fire"

04:06.705 --> 04:10.083
to win, so I'm going extreme.

04:10.083 --> 04:14.004
I'm designing something
that I can see an alien

04:14.004 --> 04:16.923
carrying in however many years.

04:16.923 --> 04:19.384
<i>I was thinking</i>
<i>this curved blade</i>

04:19.384 --> 04:21.386
<i>with a handle on the back.</i>

04:21.386 --> 04:24.139
<i>It is way outside of the box.</i>

04:24.139 --> 04:28.560
They said fantasy.
I made them fantasy.

04:28.560 --> 04:30.228
‐ Oh, my God,
I love fantasy blades.

04:30.228 --> 04:34.524
I make those all the time,
so it should be easy, right?

04:34.524 --> 04:37.235
<i>I started out making this blade</i>
<i>as a Viking blade,</i>

04:37.235 --> 04:40.071
so I'm going for a space
Viking theme.

04:40.071 --> 04:42.741
<i>So my blade was designed</i>
<i>to kill three‐headed</i>

04:42.741 --> 04:46.286
<i>tentacled purple aliens</i>
<i>from Scotland.</i>

04:46.286 --> 04:49.289
It's my realm.
I can do what I want.

04:49.289 --> 04:50.707
<i>‐ I am so polar opposite</i>

04:50.707 --> 04:53.251
<i>from the Dungeons & Dragons and</i>
<i>aliens</i>

04:53.251 --> 04:55.253
and all that stuff.

04:55.253 --> 04:59.090
I start by drawing out a design
somewhat like a sax.

04:59.090 --> 05:03.220
<i>I guess I'm kind of thinking</i>
<i>alien zombie something.</i>

05:03.220 --> 05:06.056
This is about as crazy
as my mind'll get.

05:06.056 --> 05:09.392
‐ Bladesmiths, your ten‐minute
design window has closed.

05:09.392 --> 05:12.437
Your three‐hour forge time
starts now.

05:12.437 --> 05:16.942
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:16.942 --> 05:20.654
‐ These guys have been tasked
with using meteorite.

05:20.654 --> 05:23.406
What is the constitution
of that material?

05:23.406 --> 05:24.825
‐ Well, it's mostly iron.

05:24.825 --> 05:28.411
It has varying contents
of nickel and then some cobalt.

05:28.411 --> 05:30.747
It's solid.
I mean, the ancient people,

05:30.747 --> 05:33.375
before they learned
how to smelt iron from ore,

05:33.375 --> 05:35.168
would use meteorite
to make knives.

05:35.168 --> 05:36.461
‐ Okay.

05:36.461 --> 05:39.464
‐ Canisters, it is
one of my secrets

05:39.464 --> 05:41.466
that I just don't know
how to do 'em,

05:41.466 --> 05:45.262
but the only way
is to jump in there and do it.

05:45.262 --> 05:48.265
I put white out in my canister
to start with.

05:48.265 --> 05:49.307
The purpose of the white out

05:49.307 --> 05:52.644
is to try to get the 1095
not to stick

05:52.644 --> 05:54.813
so you can cut it off
pretty easy,

05:54.813 --> 05:57.148
<i>and I know it's a soft metal,</i>

05:57.148 --> 06:00.360
<i>so I don't the meteor</i>
<i>close to the edge.</i>

06:00.360 --> 06:03.738
‐ The big challenge with this,
seeing that all that meteorite

06:03.738 --> 06:06.533
is not hardenable,
it's how you set up that can

06:06.533 --> 06:08.660
and where you're gonna
put the meteorite,

06:08.660 --> 06:11.246
and are you going to remember
where you put it

06:11.246 --> 06:13.164
once you heat that can up?

06:13.164 --> 06:15.500
‐ The time limit's not a factor
right now

06:15.500 --> 06:18.086
as long
as I get my weld to work.

06:18.086 --> 06:21.047
<i>‐ People waste a ton of time</i>
<i>liquid papering,</i>

06:21.047 --> 06:23.884
waiting for it to dry, and then
trying to remove that can,

06:23.884 --> 06:25.385
and a lot of times
they stick anyway,

06:25.385 --> 06:27.512
<i>so I'm not taking</i>
<i>the canister off.</i>

06:27.512 --> 06:30.056
<i>I'm just gonna forge</i>
<i>that soft steel right in there</i>

06:30.056 --> 06:34.019
and grind it off at the end
so I have a hardenable edge.

06:34.019 --> 06:35.478
<i>I know 1095's hardenable,</i>

06:35.478 --> 06:37.230
<i>so I'm putting that meteorite</i>
<i>in the middle.</i>

06:37.230 --> 06:39.900
<i>I need hardenable steel</i>
<i>on the edge of my knife</i>

06:39.900 --> 06:42.652
because if it's not hardenable,
it will stay soft,

06:42.652 --> 06:45.363
<i>and in the testing</i>
<i>it will get damaged.</i>

06:45.363 --> 06:47.824
‐ I like the way that Chris
is moving in here.

06:47.824 --> 06:50.702
‐ He's moving in that last
30 minutes pace.

06:50.702 --> 06:52.495
‐ Yes.
‐ He's starting there.

06:52.495 --> 06:55.248
‐ In one hour I want to have
my billet drawn out.

06:55.248 --> 06:57.542
In two hours I want
to be punching that tang,

06:57.542 --> 06:59.377
and then one hour
of solid grinding.

06:59.377 --> 07:01.171
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:01.171 --> 07:02.464
<i>‐ To make my canister,</i>

07:02.464 --> 07:04.049
<i>I'm gonna use pieces</i>
<i>of meteorite,</i>

07:04.049 --> 07:05.550
<i>and I'm gonna put them</i>
<i>in the bottom</i>

07:05.550 --> 07:07.802
<i>and try and get them to be</i>
<i>the spine of the knife,</i>

07:07.802 --> 07:10.388
<i>and I'm gonna put</i>
<i>in the 1095 powder.</i>

07:10.388 --> 07:12.015
<i>I'm doing it this way</i>
<i>so that I know</i>

07:12.015 --> 07:14.100
that my mild steel will be
in one part of the billet,

07:14.100 --> 07:16.186
and it'll be high carbon
in the rest.

07:16.186 --> 07:19.689
<i>I get my can packed up, welded,</i>
<i>and into the forge it goes.</i>

07:19.689 --> 07:20.899
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:20.899 --> 07:22.651
<i>‐ This is my first time</i>
<i>doing a canister,</i>

07:22.651 --> 07:25.070
so I'm gonna try and take
every tidbit of knowledge

07:25.070 --> 07:28.948
I know and apply it
and hope it goes right.

07:28.948 --> 07:31.951
<i>I start by putting 1095</i>
<i>in the bottom.</i>

07:31.951 --> 07:34.704
<i>I cut</i>
<i>strips with the meteorite,</i>

07:34.704 --> 07:37.332
<i>kind of layer</i>
<i>those in with 1095.</i>

07:37.332 --> 07:39.250
I figured
if I alternate them like that,

07:39.250 --> 07:43.505
I can get somewhat
of a different pattern.

07:43.505 --> 07:46.549
<i>[rock music]</i>

07:46.549 --> 07:50.595
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:50.595 --> 07:54.391
‐ I set my welds.
I feel confident in them.

07:54.391 --> 07:56.434
<i>It's time to start drawing</i>
<i>this thing out.</i>

07:56.434 --> 07:58.687
‐ Chris is looking good now.
He has to draw a billet

07:58.687 --> 08:01.189
out that's a lot longer
for his design

08:01.189 --> 08:03.274
with that big curve
and that drop edge.

08:03.274 --> 08:05.318
‐ To get this blade
at 14 inches,

08:05.318 --> 08:07.862
<i>I have to make my billet</i>
<i>26 inches long.</i>

08:07.862 --> 08:09.280
‐ That is a long billet.

08:09.280 --> 08:11.282
You could make
a sword with that.

08:11.282 --> 08:12.325
‐ I thinks it's gonna be a
while.

08:12.325 --> 08:13.952
‐ The usability, I think,

08:13.952 --> 08:16.496
is gonna be a question
in everybody's minds here.

08:16.496 --> 08:18.248
‐ We get to be part
of the fantasy.

08:18.248 --> 08:20.125
We get to make up
how to use the thing.

08:20.125 --> 08:22.669
‐ Anytime you put a extreme
bend in something

08:22.669 --> 08:24.838
that's‐‐and then
you have to strike,

08:24.838 --> 08:28.133
<i>that's a breaking point,</i>
<i>and I foresaw that,</i>

08:28.133 --> 08:31.344
<i>and I put more meat in</i>
<i>that blade</i>

08:31.344 --> 08:32.554
<i>right in that crook.</i>

08:32.554 --> 08:34.431
[laughs]

08:34.431 --> 08:40.145
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:40.145 --> 08:42.230
‐ Bladesmiths, you have just

08:42.230 --> 08:45.483
90 minutes remaining
to finish your work.

08:45.483 --> 08:47.569
‐ I got a good weld.

08:47.569 --> 08:50.655
Getting the canister off at the
moment is my biggest concern.

08:50.655 --> 08:54.200
‐ I think that what he's done
is, he's drawn out that billet,

08:54.200 --> 08:57.328
so peeling this
is gonna be a challenge.

08:57.328 --> 08:58.329
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:58.329 --> 08:59.664
<i>‐ I feel good that I got</i>
<i>a solid billet,</i>

08:59.664 --> 09:02.709
so now I want to try
and get this can off.

09:02.709 --> 09:04.461
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:04.461 --> 09:06.629
Right now this challenge
is a pain in the ass.

09:06.629 --> 09:08.339
[bleep].

09:08.339 --> 09:10.175
This can is not
coming off this billet.

09:10.175 --> 09:12.677
The white out
didn't do a damn thing.

09:12.677 --> 09:13.845
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:13.845 --> 09:15.638
<i>I made the decision</i>
<i>to not get the can off.</i>

09:15.638 --> 09:19.184
It's welded entirely on there,
so I'm just wasting time,

09:19.184 --> 09:22.937
so I'm gonna start forging
and then try and grind it off.

09:22.937 --> 09:25.356
‐ The canister is not
coming off

09:25.356 --> 09:27.067
as easy as I thought it would.

09:27.067 --> 09:28.902
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:28.902 --> 09:30.195
‐ That's got to be exhausting.

09:30.195 --> 09:31.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:31.571 --> 09:32.739
<i>‐ The clock's ticking.</i>

09:32.739 --> 09:35.241
I'm trying to not panic.

09:35.241 --> 09:37.535
<i>It's whupping me pretty hard.</i>

09:37.535 --> 09:38.787
♪ ♪

09:38.787 --> 09:39.704
‐ There you go.

09:39.704 --> 09:42.332
<i>‐ After I get the canister off,</i>

09:42.332 --> 09:46.127
<i>I'm not able to flare the end</i>
<i>out like I want to,</i>

09:46.127 --> 09:48.129
<i>because it's thin,</i>

09:48.129 --> 09:49.672
<i>but I'm still gonna have</i>

09:49.672 --> 09:51.925
a fish design when I get
through.

09:51.925 --> 09:55.428
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:55.428 --> 09:57.388
‐ [chuckling]

09:57.388 --> 09:58.723
It is working.

09:58.723 --> 10:01.684
Well, I'm drawing out my blade,
and it's looking good.

10:01.684 --> 10:06.564
<i>and then I realize that I have</i>
<i>no idea where my meteorite is.</i>

10:06.564 --> 10:07.816
[bleep].

10:07.816 --> 10:10.860
I don't remember which side
I put the high carbon on.

10:10.860 --> 10:12.779
<i>The meteorite could be</i>
<i>at the top of the billet,</i>

10:12.779 --> 10:15.365
<i>the side of the billet,</i>
<i>anywhere,</i>

10:15.365 --> 10:17.867
and I really don't
want it to be on the edge.

10:17.867 --> 10:19.369
‐ Man, oh, man.

10:19.369 --> 10:21.746
Dan lost track of where his
high carbon steel is

10:21.746 --> 10:23.414
in his blade.
‐ Uh‐oh.

10:23.414 --> 10:24.916
<i>‐ So I decide to etch my blade</i>
<i>to find out</i>

10:24.916 --> 10:26.334
where my meteorite is.

10:26.334 --> 10:28.419
‐ Oh, man.
‐ If that meteorite is

10:28.419 --> 10:31.089
on my edge, I'm screwed.
‐ Ah, here we go.

10:31.089 --> 10:32.173
There's no coming back from
that.

10:34.217 --> 10:36.219
‐ Now he can see
where everything is.

10:36.219 --> 10:38.513
‐ The nice thing about having
that meteorite

10:38.513 --> 10:42.475
with that much nickel in it,
it should pop pretty brightly.

10:42.475 --> 10:44.769
‐ Uh‐oh, that's a shame.

10:44.769 --> 10:47.939
‐ So he's got mild steel
on his edge

10:47.939 --> 10:50.775
and some high carbon steel.

10:50.775 --> 10:53.945
‐ My blade is meteorite, 1095,

10:53.945 --> 10:55.947
and they both meet at the edge.

10:55.947 --> 11:00.410
<i>It's a big deal, because</i>
<i>if both edges aren't hard,</i>

11:00.410 --> 11:03.413
the blade'll deform.
It'll break.

11:03.413 --> 11:05.582
There's really no way
for me to fix it.

11:05.582 --> 11:08.626
<i>I just hope it doesn't break.</i>

11:08.626 --> 11:10.295
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:10.295 --> 11:12.005
‐ [laughs]

11:12.005 --> 11:13.965
‐ That weird tang tail
is what's getting me.

11:13.965 --> 11:15.258
‐ That's crazy.
‐ Oh, my God.

11:15.258 --> 11:17.468
‐ It's an alien sword.

11:17.468 --> 11:19.596
‐ I hope it comes with
a user manual.

11:19.596 --> 11:21.139
‐ I would put edges
on the inside

11:21.139 --> 11:23.641
and the outside curve
of that blade. I really would.

11:23.641 --> 11:25.977
‐ This is the greatest part
about fantasy knives.

11:25.977 --> 11:27.270
‐ The sky's the limit.

11:27.270 --> 11:28.313
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:28.313 --> 11:30.231
<i>‐ I want to quench</i>
<i>just the edge,</i>

11:30.231 --> 11:32.609
but the quench tank
won't allow that,

11:32.609 --> 11:34.652
so I'm gonna have to quench
the whole blade.

11:34.652 --> 11:35.945
Ooh‐hoo.

11:35.945 --> 11:37.572
<i>I want that blade to be hard.</i>

11:37.572 --> 11:39.240
I want that blade
to be straight.

11:39.240 --> 11:41.117
<i>It's not hard.</i>

