I've got to get a edge
on it that will cut,

22:43.487 --> 22:47.783
<i>but I don't want too fine</i>
<i>of a edge that it might chip.</i>

22:47.783 --> 22:51.453
I don't have a point on it,
but I've got a fish mouth,

22:51.453 --> 22:54.790
<i>actually, two points,</i>
<i>so what I've done is,</i>

22:54.790 --> 22:58.377
I've made all of my ends sharp,

22:58.377 --> 23:02.047
so it's more like a razor blade
than a point.

23:02.047 --> 23:04.091
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths!

23:04.091 --> 23:07.052
‐ Right now my stress level
is through the roof.

23:07.052 --> 23:10.180
‐ So Chris just pulled
his blade out of the acid etch.

23:10.180 --> 23:13.058
‐ The clock's ticking down.
Blade is etched.

23:13.058 --> 23:17.187
I'm getting my final edge
on it, polishing up the pommel.

23:17.187 --> 23:18.439
Ow.
‐ Oh.

23:18.439 --> 23:20.524
‐ The blade catches
the grinder wheel.

23:20.524 --> 23:22.484
‐ Oh, boy.
‐ And I'm bleeding all over

23:22.484 --> 23:24.820
my blade
and all over The Forge.

23:24.820 --> 23:26.113
‐ I'm just gonna tape it,
all right?

23:26.113 --> 23:27.281
‐ Okay, that's great.

23:27.281 --> 23:28.908
‐ We got Chris getting bandaged
up by the medic,

23:28.908 --> 23:32.870
and he's got an eye
on the clock at the same time.

23:32.870 --> 23:35.414
Dan's blade is so thin.

23:35.414 --> 23:38.042
‐ Yeah.
‐ Whew.

23:38.042 --> 23:40.169
‐ Thank you.
My thumb is taped up.

23:40.169 --> 23:42.421
<i>I'm gonna use every second</i>
<i>of that clock.</i>

23:42.421 --> 23:44.548
I'm gonna go until
Wil tells me to stop.

23:44.548 --> 23:46.592
‐ Five, four,

23:46.592 --> 23:50.387
three, two, one, bladesmiths,

23:50.387 --> 23:51.722
stop what you're doing.

23:51.722 --> 23:55.768
This second round
of competition is over.

23:55.768 --> 23:57.561
‐ Good job.
<i>‐ Now that I'm done,</i>

23:57.561 --> 23:59.563
I'm nervous about my design.

23:59.563 --> 24:01.982
I went extreme,
and I don't know

24:01.982 --> 24:03.567
if that's gonna come back
and bite me in the ass.

24:03.567 --> 24:04.693
I don't know.

24:04.693 --> 24:06.946
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the strength test.

24:06.946 --> 24:09.239
<i>To test the strength</i>
<i>and durability of your blades</i>

24:09.239 --> 24:10.574
<i>as well</i>
<i>as the overall construction</i>

24:10.574 --> 24:11.909
<i>of your fantasy knives,</i>

24:11.909 --> 24:14.411
I will be chopping them
into this odd‐looking armor.

24:14.411 --> 24:16.497
Remember,
this test is all about

24:16.497 --> 24:17.873
what the armor
does to your blades

24:17.873 --> 24:19.583
and not what your blades
do to the armor.

24:19.583 --> 24:20.709
Dan, you're up first.
You ready?

24:20.709 --> 24:22.252
‐ Yup.
‐ All right.

24:22.252 --> 24:23.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:23.629 --> 24:25.923
<i>‐ Oh, God, this is the worst</i>
<i>feeling ever.</i>

24:25.923 --> 24:27.841
My stomach just went up
to my throat.

24:27.841 --> 24:29.927
Half my edge
is high carbon steel,

24:29.927 --> 24:31.929
<i>and the other half</i>
<i>is meteorite.</i>

24:31.929 --> 24:34.848
It looks good, but I don't
think it's gonna hold up.

24:34.848 --> 24:41.939
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:51.657 --> 24:53.826
‐ Well, Dan,
first things first,

24:53.826 --> 24:55.035
your knife held together.

24:55.035 --> 24:57.663
Everything's still tight.
There's no wiggling.

24:57.663 --> 24:59.081
The edge, however,

24:59.081 --> 25:02.459
there's three major sections
of deformation.

25:02.459 --> 25:05.004
You can see the steel is
sticking up pretty high here.

25:05.004 --> 25:06.630
It's kind of curled around.

25:06.630 --> 25:08.465
That all being said,
I think you did

25:08.465 --> 25:11.343
a really interesting
fantasy‐looking blade,

25:11.343 --> 25:14.471
and this part up here
where it becomes big and proud,

25:14.471 --> 25:16.932
it really penetrated the armor
really well right there.

25:16.932 --> 25:18.809
It's interesting‐looking
and functional

25:18.809 --> 25:20.144
at the same time, so well done.

25:20.144 --> 25:21.812
‐ Thank you.
‐ Randy, you're up.

25:21.812 --> 25:25.524
How you feeling?
‐ Not really ready.

25:25.524 --> 25:26.608
‐ Yeah, we're gonna
do it anyway.

25:26.608 --> 25:27.943
<i>‐ I'm a little worried.</i>

25:27.943 --> 25:30.487
<i>Dan's blade</i>
<i>took a lot of damage,</i>

25:30.487 --> 25:33.490
<i>and I feel like I may be</i>
<i>right there with him.</i>

25:33.490 --> 25:36.910
I want to close my eyes,
and I just don't want to look.

25:36.910 --> 25:44.001
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:50.674 --> 25:51.967
Whew.

25:51.967 --> 25:55.095
‐ Well, Randy, this is a‐‐it's
got a lot of mass

25:55.095 --> 25:57.181
to this thing.
This is a heavy knife.

25:57.181 --> 25:59.183
Your blade held up really well.

25:59.183 --> 26:02.436
There's some minor
chipping here and here,

26:02.436 --> 26:04.063
but the edge geometry
you put on that

26:04.063 --> 26:07.232
is perfect
for a chopping test like this.

26:07.232 --> 26:10.110
The handle is comfortable
to hold,

26:10.110 --> 26:13.697
but it is a little bit easy
to lose control.

26:13.697 --> 26:15.115
That aside,

26:15.115 --> 26:16.867
I like that you used
the meteorite for the guard.

26:16.867 --> 26:20.704
I think it really adds to the
fantasy nature of the knife,

26:20.704 --> 26:22.456
so in all, well done.

26:22.456 --> 26:23.999
‐ Thank you.
‐ Chris, you're up next.

26:23.999 --> 26:25.584
Are you ready?
‐ I'm ready.

26:25.584 --> 26:27.002
‐ I'm excited to
swing this thing.

26:27.002 --> 26:29.046
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:29.046 --> 26:30.464
<i>‐ My knees are shaking.</i>

26:30.464 --> 26:32.925
<i>My palms are sweating.</i>
<i>My heart is thumping.</i>

26:32.925 --> 26:36.386
<i>What I'm worried about</i>
<i>is my design.</i>

26:36.386 --> 26:38.555
<i>I've never seen one</i>
<i>like my blade.</i>

26:38.555 --> 26:39.973
<i>I've never seen one tested.</i>

26:39.973 --> 26:41.350
I've never seen one
swing or wielded.

26:41.350 --> 26:43.560
I don't know where it's gonna
fail, if it's gonna fail.

26:43.560 --> 26:45.354
<i>It may do fantastic.</i>
<i>I don't know.</i>

26:47.815 --> 26:54.905
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:02.412 --> 27:05.290
‐ Well, Chris, this is why
I wore a glove.

27:05.290 --> 27:07.251
I'm kind of stuck in there.

27:07.251 --> 27:08.794
For the first couple strikes
it was fun to swing,

27:08.794 --> 27:11.463
I'll give you that,
that's for sure.

27:11.463 --> 27:13.966
It is bent up this way here,

27:13.966 --> 27:16.093
but more importantly,
right down here

27:16.093 --> 27:17.678
where the blade
meets the handle

27:17.678 --> 27:20.973
is where it pulled away
from the guard at that spot.

27:20.973 --> 27:22.432
I'm guessing your tang
right there,

27:22.432 --> 27:24.017
it just wasn't wide enough
to support

27:24.017 --> 27:27.187
this amount of stress, and the
whole handle will go over,

27:27.187 --> 27:28.438
and I just don't feel
comfortable testing

27:28.438 --> 27:30.107
this weapon anymore.

27:30.107 --> 27:32.609
‐ I understand.

27:32.609 --> 27:33.652
‐ All right, Chris,

27:33.652 --> 27:35.779
of all of our smiths
in this competition,

27:35.779 --> 27:39.116
you embraced this challenge
the most wholeheartedly,

27:39.116 --> 27:42.953
but unfortunately, it presents
a clear and present danger

27:42.953 --> 27:44.454
to the end user,

27:44.454 --> 27:47.249
and for that reason we cannot
continue testing your blade,

27:47.249 --> 27:50.460
and I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

27:50.460 --> 27:52.588
<i>‐ I went all‐out</i>
<i>with my design.</i>

27:52.588 --> 27:54.464
I embraced that challenge.

27:54.464 --> 27:56.967
<i>My son and I have</i>
<i>a very competitive</i>

27:56.967 --> 27:58.468
<i>bladesmithing relationship.</i>

27:58.468 --> 27:59.928
<i>We compete all the time,</i>

27:59.928 --> 28:02.180
<i>so‐‐and he wants to come</i>
<i>to "Forged in Fire"</i>

28:02.180 --> 28:03.390
when he turns 18.

28:03.390 --> 28:05.183
I set a pretty big bar
for him to meet,

28:05.183 --> 28:08.353
<i>but I'm excited for him</i>
<i>to get this experience.</i>

28:08.353 --> 28:09.771
<i>First thing I do</i>
<i>when I get home is,</i>

28:09.771 --> 28:12.316
I'm gonna hug my wife
and kiss my dog,

28:12.316 --> 28:15.485
but I don't have
a dog or a wife.

28:15.485 --> 28:18.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:18.822 --> 28:20.699
‐ Dan, Randy,
when you came here,

28:20.699 --> 28:22.659
we asked you
to make fantasy blades.

28:22.659 --> 28:24.995
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

28:24.995 --> 28:27.539
to make this fantastic weapon,

28:27.539 --> 28:31.126
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:31.126 --> 28:33.962
Attila the Hun's Sword of Mars.

28:33.962 --> 28:36.590
‐ [laughs]

28:36.590 --> 28:37.716
Yes.

28:37.716 --> 28:39.051
<i>‐ Known as the scourge of God,</i>

28:39.051 --> 28:40.552
<i>Attila the Hun</i>
<i>was one of the most</i>

28:40.552 --> 28:42.179
<i>feared conquerors in history.</i>

28:42.179 --> 28:43.931
<i>The leader</i>
<i>of the Hunnic Empire,</i>

28:43.931 --> 28:45.515
<i>his group of nomadic tribes</i>

28:45.515 --> 28:48.310
<i>wreaked havoc across Europe</i>
<i>during the fifth century.</i>

28:48.310 --> 28:50.520
<i>Though he was once</i>
<i>a great ally to them,</i>

28:50.520 --> 28:51.980
<i>he plagued Roman territories,</i>

28:51.980 --> 28:54.524
<i>sacking major cities</i>
<i>like Constantinople.</i>

28:54.524 --> 28:56.860
<i>Legend states that Attila</i>
<i>was given the Sword of Mars</i>

28:56.860 --> 28:58.737
<i>by a herdsman,</i>
<i>fulfilling a prophecy</i>

28:58.737 --> 29:00.614
<i>and a direct sign</i>
<i>from the Roman war</i>

29:00.614 --> 29:02.699
<i>god Mars of his divine rule.</i>

29:02.699 --> 29:04.368
<i>The lethal weapon</i>
<i>featured a curved handle</i>

29:04.368 --> 29:07.329
<i>with a spear point tip that</i>
<i>gave it exceptional control,</i>

29:07.329 --> 29:09.498
<i>allowing for accurate</i>
<i>and brutal thrusts.</i>

29:09.498 --> 29:11.875
<i>After Attila's death</i>
<i>in the year 453,</i>

29:11.875 --> 29:13.669
<i>the Hunnic Empire</i>
<i>quickly dissolved.</i>

29:13.669 --> 29:16.797
<i>However, the story of Attila's</i>
<i>many conquests still live on</i>

29:16.797 --> 29:19.383
<i>through the television</i>
<i>miniseries "Attila."</i>

29:19.383 --> 29:21.009
This blade must have
a spear tip

29:21.009 --> 29:24.221
and a false edge that runs
half the length of the spine.

29:24.221 --> 29:27.891
In addition, it must have
a ball pommel, drop handle,

29:27.891 --> 29:30.644
and a finial ball guard.

29:30.644 --> 29:32.562
‐ What have I gotten myself
into?

29:32.562 --> 29:34.231
<i>That blade looks huge.</i>

29:34.231 --> 29:35.857
‐ Bladesmiths, you'll have
four days at your home

29:35.857 --> 29:38.026
forges in which
to complete this challenge.

29:38.026 --> 29:40.779
At the end of those four days,
you'll return and present

29:40.779 --> 29:43.240
your swords
to our panel of expert judges,

29:43.240 --> 29:44.992
and after they've thoroughly
tested them,

29:44.992 --> 29:48.370
they'll declare one of you
a "Forged in Fire" champion,

29:48.370 --> 29:52.666
and you'll walk out of here
with a check for $10,000.

29:52.666 --> 29:53.834
Good luck, bladesmiths.

29:53.834 --> 29:57.921
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:57.921 --> 29:59.131
<i>‐ I'm one of</i>
<i>the youngest contestants</i>

29:59.131 --> 30:00.382
<i>on "Forged in Fire."</i>

30:00.382 --> 30:02.509
Randy, he's about three
to four times my age,

30:02.509 --> 30:04.678
so I'd like to see
how our skills stack up,

30:04.678 --> 30:05.971
sort of new versus old.

30:05.971 --> 30:08.265
<i>So I'm gonna be chopping up</i>
<i>this old muscle car</i>

30:08.265 --> 30:09.599
<i>to get the leaf springs out,</i>

30:09.599 --> 30:10.976
<i>and that's gonna be the steel</i>
<i>for my sword.</i>

30:10.976 --> 30:12.894
I love working with
that sort of stuff.

30:12.894 --> 30:15.397
There's my steel.

30:15.397 --> 30:17.441
<i>So my game plan for today</i>

30:17.441 --> 30:20.110
<i>is basically get the blade</i>
<i>rough forged out</i>

30:20.110 --> 30:23.280
<i>and maybe even ground a little</i>
<i>bit if I have enough time.</i>

30:23.280 --> 30:25.323
<i>I don't have a power hammer</i>
<i>or a press.</i>

30:25.323 --> 30:27.409
This is my power hammer.

30:27.409 --> 30:29.202
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:29.202 --> 30:30.954
<i>The plan is to quench tomorrow.</i>

30:30.954 --> 30:31.955
<i>I'm concerned for the time.</i>

30:31.955 --> 30:33.790
It's not as much time
as I'd like,

30:33.790 --> 30:36.126
but it's just barely
enough time to get it done.

30:36.126 --> 30:37.044
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:37.044 --> 30:38.628
<i>‐ I'm back at my home forge,</i>

30:38.628 --> 30:41.798
<i>and I'm gonna be making</i>
<i>this sword out of Damascus.</i>

30:41.798 --> 30:46.094
I'm making it Damascus
to catch the judges' eyes.

30:46.094 --> 30:48.680
<i>Damascus, you can have</i>
<i>all kinds of problems.</i>

30:48.680 --> 30:51.433
<i>It could fail on me,</i>
<i>but I'm gonna take a chance</i>

30:51.433 --> 30:53.351
<i>and see where</i>
<i>this one comes out.</i>

30:53.351 --> 30:55.312
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:55.312 --> 30:57.147
<i>I've stretched my billet out,</i>

30:57.147 --> 30:59.733
<i>and I cut it</i>
<i>in six equal pieces.</i>

30:59.733 --> 31:01.943
<i>Now I'm welding it back</i>
<i>together to go back</i>

31:01.943 --> 31:04.696
<i>in the forge and forge weld it,</i>
<i>then stretch it out.</i>

31:04.696 --> 31:07.449
<i>I'll have 78 layers</i>
<i>when I get through,</i>

31:07.449 --> 31:09.326
<i>and hopefully a pretty pattern.</i>

31:09.326 --> 31:11.620
<i>If it sets well, I'm home free.</i>

31:11.620 --> 31:13.413
<i>I hope it holds.</i>

31:13.413 --> 31:16.374
It's scrap.
The weld didn't hold.

31:16.374 --> 31:19.211
It's got a void. I'm afraid
if I keep fooling with it,

31:19.211 --> 31:21.588
I'm gonna run out of metal,

31:21.588 --> 31:26.510
so I'm gonna scrap it
and start all over.

31:26.510 --> 31:30.347
I got 3 1/2 hours
of dead nothing.

31:30.347 --> 31:34.601
<i>Tomorrow's gonna really be</i>
<i>what makes or breaks the deal.</i>

31:34.601 --> 31:35.977
I'm gonna have to push it.

31:35.977 --> 31:37.854
<i>‐ This is the start of day two.</i>

31:37.854 --> 31:39.940
I want to get the heat treat
and temper out of the way

31:39.940 --> 31:42.317
<i>and done so I can start working</i>
<i>on the finer details</i>

31:42.317 --> 31:43.401
<i>of this blade.</i>

31:43.401 --> 31:44.820
This one's for the money.

31:44.820 --> 31:47.114
There's a lot of concerns when
you make a blade this long,

31:47.114 --> 31:49.199
<i>because if you don't have it</i>
<i>even and flat,</i>

31:49.199 --> 31:53.703
<i>that gives it more of a chance</i>
<i>to warp in the quench.</i>

31:53.703 --> 31:55.580
I pull it out of the oil.

31:55.580 --> 31:58.041
The blade's got a slight warp
in it, but it's hard.

31:58.041 --> 32:00.043
<i>I still have enough time</i>
<i>to bend it.</i>

32:00.043 --> 32:03.213
<i>It's just a very small window.</i>

32:03.213 --> 32:05.757
<i>And then I'm there</i>
<i>holding two blades.</i>

32:05.757 --> 32:08.093
Damn it.
This sucks.

32:09.052 --> 32:10.053
it.

32:10.053 --> 32:11.721
There goes almost
a full day of work,

32:11.721 --> 32:13.557
<i>Time is of the essence.</i>

32:13.557 --> 32:17.144
I've got to get started
on another blade now.

32:17.144 --> 32:19.020
This is really gonna suck.

32:19.020 --> 32:23.066
‐ On day two I got my new blade
stretched out.

32:23.066 --> 32:26.945
I wound up with 13 layers
instead of 78.

32:26.945 --> 32:28.572
<i>Today I'm starting off</i>

32:28.572 --> 32:33.076
fitting these ball spindles to
my guard.

32:33.076 --> 32:34.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:34.703 --> 32:37.414
I got my ball spindle made.

32:37.414 --> 32:38.915
Just don't look good.

32:38.915 --> 32:41.209
It's been a struggle
to get it this far,

32:41.209 --> 32:43.753
but I believe
I'm gonna start it all over,

32:43.753 --> 32:46.214
because it's just got
too much space in it.

32:46.214 --> 32:49.134
<i>This guard is kind of</i>
<i>getting to me.</i>

32:49.134 --> 32:52.262
It's really beginning
to get on my nerves.

32:52.262 --> 32:54.097
<i>It's time to trash this.</i>

32:54.097 --> 32:56.808
<i>I need this to work,</i>
<i>because if it don't,</i>

32:56.808 --> 33:01.188
I don't know that I'll have
enough time to start all over.

33:01.188 --> 33:03.106
<i>‐ It's the start of day four.</i>

33:03.106 --> 33:04.608
<i>I lost time</i>
<i>with my first blade.</i>

33:04.608 --> 33:05.942
Time's winding down now.

33:05.942 --> 33:08.445
I want to make sure that
this is spot‐on for the judges.

33:08.445 --> 33:11.907
The tang's a little bent,
but it should be working.

33:11.907 --> 33:15.452
<i>Now I'm gonna start work</i>
<i>on my handle,</i>

33:15.452 --> 33:17.245
<i>which is going to be made</i>
<i>out of this little dolphin</i>

33:17.245 --> 33:18.663
<i>that I got from a thrift store.</i>

33:18.663 --> 33:20.373
I like to find a use
for everything.

33:20.373 --> 33:22.751
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:22.751 --> 33:24.961
I want to get the tang burned
in all the way.

33:24.961 --> 33:26.713
You see how it's not smoking?

33:26.713 --> 33:29.174
That means the wood's not
touching any part that's hot.

33:29.174 --> 33:31.801
I couldn't get the tang
hot enough to burn in,

33:31.801 --> 33:34.638
so the only thing keeping me
from going all the way up

33:34.638 --> 33:36.139
is the width here,

33:36.139 --> 33:37.265
<i>so I've got to stick it in the</i>
<i>drill press</i>

33:37.265 --> 33:39.643
<i>and then drill out</i>
<i>a little bit.</i>

33:39.643 --> 33:41.978
I fit the handle
and epoxy it in.

33:41.978 --> 33:44.397
Once it's on there,
it's permanent.

33:44.397 --> 33:45.982
I can't go back.

33:45.982 --> 33:49.736
This is insanely nerve‐racking.

33:49.736 --> 33:52.822
If my fit up is loose
whatsoever, I could go home.

33:52.822 --> 33:56.034
I wish I had more time
to make it a little bit better.

33:56.034 --> 33:58.245
Oop,
there goes your cushion.

33:58.245 --> 34:01.206
<i>‐ It's the last day.</i>

34:01.206 --> 34:05.043
I've had a few setbacks,
but I'm almost done.

34:05.043 --> 34:09.839
I'm going to put some jewels
in the handle.

34:09.839 --> 34:11.675
<i>Attila, he was a great leader,</i>

34:11.675 --> 34:14.844
<i>and I think the jewels</i>
<i>will be something</i>

34:14.844 --> 34:18.139
<i>that he would have</i>
<i>in his sword.</i>

34:18.139 --> 34:21.017
<i>I've got my jewels in it.</i>
<i>There's one thing left to do,</i>

34:21.017 --> 34:23.478
etch it and see
what kind of pattern I've got.

34:23.478 --> 34:24.813
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:24.813 --> 34:26.690
Oh, yeah.

34:26.690 --> 34:28.525
<i>The pattern turned out well.</i>

34:28.525 --> 34:31.111
<i>I don't believe</i>
<i>I could have done any better</i>

34:31.111 --> 34:32.779
<i>if I had more layers.</i>

34:32.779 --> 34:33.947
I think I've built a sword

34:33.947 --> 34:36.616
that Attila the Hun
would be proud of.

34:36.616 --> 34:41.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:41.579 --> 34:43.581
‐ Dan, Randy,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:43.581 --> 34:46.167
You guys have had four days
at your home forges to work

34:46.167 --> 34:51.256
on your version of Attila
the Hun's Sword of Mars.

34:51.256 --> 34:52.549
Dan, how'd it go?

34:52.549 --> 34:55.885
‐ So my blade is made
from 5160 spring steel.

34:55.885 --> 34:57.429
<i>The pommel and guard are brass,</i>

34:57.429 --> 35:00.932
<i>and the handle is made</i>
<i>from African mahogany.</i>

35:00.932 --> 35:02.559
Everything is repurposed.

35:02.559 --> 35:04.060
‐ All right,
Randy, how'd it go for you?

35:04.060 --> 35:05.687
‐ Had to start over
a couple times,

35:05.687 --> 35:07.772
but it went good after that.

35:07.772 --> 35:10.900
<i>It's made from 5160 and 15N20.</i>

35:10.900 --> 35:13.486
<i>The ball is made</i>
<i>from a hammer head.</i>

35:13.486 --> 35:17.240
<i>The guard is made</i>
<i>from a pair of tongs,</i>

35:17.240 --> 35:21.911
<i>and the handle</i>
<i>is a ten‐piece exotic woods.</i>

35:21.911 --> 35:24.080
‐ All right, gentlemen,
we're gonna put your weapons

35:24.080 --> 35:25.665
through
a series of three tests.

35:25.665 --> 35:27.375
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

35:27.375 --> 35:29.919
and up first, the kill test.
Doug?

35:29.919 --> 35:31.921
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:31.921 --> 35:33.423
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
to find out

35:33.423 --> 35:35.759
what kind of lethal damage
your weapon will do,

35:35.759 --> 35:39.054
I will deliver killing blows
on this ballistics dummy.

35:39.054 --> 35:40.221
Randy, you're up first.
You ready?

35:40.221 --> 35:42.265
‐ I am.
‐ Let's do this.

35:42.265 --> 35:44.601
<i>‐ I don't know what to expect,</i>

35:44.601 --> 35:46.603
and
I know they gonna hit it hard.

35:46.603 --> 35:48.438
<i>I'm a little bit jibbery.</i>

35:48.438 --> 35:50.940
<i>My legs want to give out</i>
<i>from under me a little bit,</i>

35:50.940 --> 35:53.485
but I think I'll be okay.

35:54.778 --> 36:01.826
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:07.123 --> 36:10.126
‐ Nice.

36:10.126 --> 36:14.631
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:14.631 --> 36:16.257
‐ [laughs]

36:16.257 --> 36:18.009
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:18.009 --> 36:20.178
‐ All right, Randy, let's talk
about your Sword of Mars here.

36:20.178 --> 36:23.973
First up, the Damascus pattern
you have here is gorgeous.

36:23.973 --> 36:25.433
‐ Thank you.
‐ The weapon design

36:25.433 --> 36:28.478
is very aggressive
for thrusting and slashing.

36:28.478 --> 36:32.023
Now, your handle construction,
if you reverse this,

36:32.023 --> 36:34.526
it'll be easier
to have something to lock onto.

36:34.526 --> 36:36.277
The fact that the flare
is right here,

36:36.277 --> 36:39.739
forcing my hand to open up if
I want to marry into the hilt.

36:39.739 --> 36:41.282
This is a very sharp weapon.

36:41.282 --> 36:43.868
The tip pierces
all the way through.

36:43.868 --> 36:45.537
It cuts on the way out.

36:45.537 --> 36:49.124
It's pointy and scary,
and it will KEAL.

36:49.124 --> 36:50.625
‐ Thank you.
‐ Good job.

36:50.625 --> 36:52.252
All right, Dan,
it is your turn. You ready?

36:52.252 --> 36:53.753
‐ Hell, yeah.
‐ Let's do this.

36:53.753 --> 36:55.547
‐ I was hoping the kill test
would be a dummy.

36:55.547 --> 36:57.674
I know heads will roll.

36:57.674 --> 36:59.300
<i>I'm feeling really confident.</i>

36:59.300 --> 37:00.760
I want to see
what this thing does.

37:00.760 --> 37:07.851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:24.701 --> 37:26.661
‐ All right, Dan, let's talk
about your weapon here.

37:26.661 --> 37:28.455
I love the balance
of your blade.

37:28.455 --> 37:31.833
When I go forward,
it's not hard to pull back

37:31.833 --> 37:33.376
to go in again
for another kill.

37:33.376 --> 37:36.045
Now, your handle construction,
it's curved enough

37:36.045 --> 37:37.881
to where it doesn't want
to fly out of my hand.

37:37.881 --> 37:40.175
It's got a good grip
and control for this.

37:40.175 --> 37:42.886
Your edge allows
for very deep cuts

37:42.886 --> 37:44.512
into the abdomen right there.

37:44.512 --> 37:48.016
The only issue we have is that
your tip picked up a bend

37:48.016 --> 37:50.059
when it chopped into the spine,

37:50.059 --> 37:52.937
but your weapon, sir,
will KEAL.

37:52.937 --> 37:54.314
‐ Thank you.

37:54.314 --> 37:56.191
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:56.191 --> 37:58.610
‐ All right, gentlemen, it's
time for the strength test.

37:58.610 --> 38:01.905
Now, Attila's armies were
basically one large cavalry,

38:01.905 --> 38:03.531
and through
his military campaigns

38:03.531 --> 38:06.409
he revolutionized the use
of horse in military conflicts,

38:06.409 --> 38:08.578
so to test the strength
and durability of your blades,

38:08.578 --> 38:10.497
I'll be chopping
into these horse skulls.

38:10.497 --> 38:11.915
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:11.915 --> 38:13.583
Randy, you're up first.
Are you ready?

38:13.583 --> 38:16.336
‐ I guess so.
‐ Okay.

38:16.336 --> 38:20.089
I designed my blade
with a sharp, sharp edge,

38:20.089 --> 38:21.925
<i>and I'm a little worried.</i>

38:21.925 --> 38:24.302
<i>My stomach's up in my throat</i>
<i>a little bit.</i>

38:43.071 --> 38:44.739
Wow.

38:44.739 --> 38:47.534
‐ Okay, so right off the bat,

38:47.534 --> 38:50.787
the biggest thing is
that this section from right

38:50.787 --> 38:55.208
about here to here
has lost its edge.

38:55.208 --> 38:59.504
There's a couple
of small rolls.

38:59.504 --> 39:01.464
Blade's still straight.
It's all in one piece.

39:01.464 --> 39:04.133
It's still solid. Nicely done.
It's a very strong blade.

39:04.133 --> 39:05.593
‐ Thank you.
‐ All right, Dan,

39:05.593 --> 39:07.053
are you ready?

39:07.053 --> 39:10.265
‐ No, but let's do it.
‐ Everybody says that.

39:10.265 --> 39:13.226
<i>‐ The first test bent my blade,</i>
<i>so I'm feeling a little bit</i>

39:13.226 --> 39:15.144
<i>of fear</i>
<i>going into the strength test.</i>

39:15.144 --> 39:16.604
This will kill blades.

39:16.604 --> 39:19.482
<i>It's a scary, brutal thing.</i>

39:19.482 --> 39:21.025
♪ ♪

39:21.025 --> 39:23.486
Whew.

39:23.486 --> 39:30.618
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:37.250 --> 39:38.334
‐ Wow.

39:38.334 --> 39:41.254
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:41.254 --> 39:42.422
‐ At the guard.

39:42.422 --> 39:47.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:47.760 --> 39:50.680
‐ Okay, so before we get
to the obvious,

39:50.680 --> 39:52.974
I really like the design
of your blade.

39:52.974 --> 39:54.183
It's got a great weight to it.

39:54.183 --> 39:56.144
It had a really good
feel in my hand.

39:56.144 --> 39:58.313
The balance was really nice.

39:58.313 --> 40:01.482
See all that space
around your tang?

40:01.482 --> 40:05.320
With that room for that blade
to move inside the guard,

40:05.320 --> 40:07.155
it could just create
so much stress

40:07.155 --> 40:10.325
that it cut loose
right there at the corner.

40:10.325 --> 40:12.911
If it were all tight,
there wouldn't be any stress.

40:12.911 --> 40:15.038
There's no discoloration here,
so it's not that there were‐‐

40:15.038 --> 40:18.207
there was a crack here before.
The grain structure looks fine.

40:18.207 --> 40:21.002
It was a well‐designed piece,
but obvious flaw.

40:21.002 --> 40:23.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:23.713 --> 40:25.048
‐ Dan, unfortunately,

40:25.048 --> 40:26.382
your blade suffered
a catastrophic failure

40:26.382 --> 40:28.176
in the middle
of our strength test,

40:28.176 --> 40:30.720
which means that we can
no longer test it,

40:30.720 --> 40:33.222
and I'd like to invite you
to shake our hands,

40:33.222 --> 40:35.099
shake your competitor's hands,

40:35.099 --> 40:37.310
and then please
leave The Forge.

40:37.310 --> 40:39.228
<i>‐ It hurts, but my sword</i>
<i>breaking</i>

40:39.228 --> 40:40.521
<i>it's gonna be a reminder</i>

40:40.521 --> 40:42.315
that I have
to push harder and be better.

40:42.315 --> 40:44.484
‐ Dan, keep up the work.
It's a good sword.

40:44.484 --> 40:47.236
‐ I came here to prove that
I can compete with the big dogs

40:47.236 --> 40:48.529
<i>and that I do know</i>
<i>what I'm doing,</i>

40:48.529 --> 40:51.908
<i>and I think I might</i>
<i>have accomplished that.</i>

40:51.908 --> 40:55.244
‐ Randy, the strength
and efficiency of your weapon

40:55.244 --> 40:56.913
in the kill test
have earned you the title

40:56.913 --> 41:00.208
of "Forged in Fire" champion
and a check for how much?

41:00.208 --> 41:02.585
‐ $10,000.
‐ That's right, $10,000.

41:02.585 --> 41:04.003
Good job, brother.

41:04.003 --> 41:05.254
<i>‐ I won "Forged in Fire."</i>

41:05.254 --> 41:06.214
It's reality.

41:06.214 --> 41:07.757
‐ How do you feel?
‐ Good.

41:07.757 --> 41:11.552
<i>To be a champion and be</i>
<i>recognized as a good bladesmith</i>

41:11.552 --> 41:13.429
<i>is real good.</i>

41:13.429 --> 41:16.265
This is my happy
and excited face...

41:16.265 --> 41:17.725
‐ Well done, sir.
‐ Thank you.

41:17.725 --> 41:19.227
If you didn't recognize it.

